		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Satyagraha</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For the opera, see <a href="/wiki/Satyagraha_(opera)" title="Satyagraha (opera)">Satyagraha (opera)</a>.</div>
<p><b>Satyagraha</b> (<a href="/wiki/Sanskrit_language" title="Sanskrit language" class="mw-redirect">Sanskrit</a>: <span lang="sa" xml:lang="sa">सत्याग्रह</span> <span lang="sa-Latn" title="International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration" class="Unicode" style="white-space:normal; text-decoration: none" xml:lang="sa-Latn"><i>satyāgraha</i></span>) is a philosophy and practice of <a href="/wiki/Nonviolent_resistance" title="Nonviolent resistance">nonviolent resistance</a> developed by <a href="/wiki/Mohandas_Karamchand_Gandhi" title="Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi">Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi</a> (also known as "Mahatma" Gandhi). Gandhi deployed satyagraha in campaigns for <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indian</a> independence and also during his earlier struggles in <a href="/wiki/South_Africa" title="South Africa">South Africa</a>. Satyagraha theory also influenced <a href="/wiki/Martin_Luther_King,_Jr." title="Martin Luther King, Jr.">Martin Luther King, Jr.</a> during the campaigns he led during the <a href="/wiki/Civil_rights_movement" title="Civil rights movement">civil rights movement</a> in the United States.</p>
